1. For **Timestamp format for component logs**, select one of the following:
  <p class='note breaking'><strong>Breaking Change:</strong> If you are upgrading from <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> v2.9, update any external monitoring configuration you use to account for the correct new timestamp format after configuring <strong>Timestamp format for component logs</strong>. For more information, see <a href='https://docs.pivotal.io/platform/2-10/release-notes/breaking-changes.html#timestamps'>Timestamp Format for Component Logs Replaces Timestamp Format for Diego Logs</a> in <em><%= vars.ops_manager %> and Runtime Breaking Changes</em>.</p>
  + (Recommended) **Converge to human-readable RFC3339 format**: Every <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> component that supports RFC3339 timestamps uses this format in their logs.
  The RFC3339 format uses Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) and provides up to nine points of precision.
  For more information, see [RFC3339](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3339).<br><br>For example:
      + 2019-11-21T22:16:18.750673404Z
      + 2019-11-21T22:16:18.750000000Z
  <p class="note"><strong>Note</strong>: For a current list of components that use the RFC3339 timestamp format, see <a href="https://docs.pivotal.io/platform/<%= vars.current_major_version.sub('.', '-') %>/release-notes/runtime-rn.html">VMware Tanzu Application Service for VMs v2.10 Release Notes</a>.</p>
  + **Maintain previous format**: <%= vars.app_runtime_abbr %> component logs use their previous timestamp format. <%= vars.company_name %> recommends only selecting this option if you have scripts that require logs that use the previous timestamp format.

1. Click **Save**.

